[1
Date: Fri, 31 Jul 1998 03:52:46 PDT
From: Hakon Haaheim <mildemoses@hotmail.com>

A few words and thoughts about the provoking posting of Thu, 30 Jul. 1998
entitled "body piercing, tatooing
& infection".
"All John Doe wanted was a $45 removal of his appendix, but he ended up
with a $125,000 liver transplant." Would ProMED-mail print anything like
this? Most infectious organisms demand a site of entry and even the
slightest insight in microbial and infectious disease tells there is a rise
in the risk of infection when rupture of skin occurs.
Semmelweiss could have said: "dirty hands don't mingle with needles and
skin". Hygienic measures are long time ago acknowledged a major factor in
the prevention of infectious diseases. This also applies for tattooing
organisations and every tattoo artist belonging to a professional laud. A
potential tattoo customer might check out the reputation and skills of the
artist. He also might check the tattooing equipment, find out whether
needles are used twice etc.
ProMED-mail, or the moderators, should keep up the usually good work with
updated epidemic details, possible sources of transmission and world wide
news. Sensational stuff like statements of the "If anybody's thinking of
getting a tattoo, I'd say, 'Don't,'" kind should be reserved magazines and
newspapers I don't pay much attention. An epidemic spreading from a tattoo
shop is good stuff, distribute those stories and not ones describing a
juvenile of poor destiny choosing the tattoo of a wolf standing on a rock
howling at the moon because "it just stuck out", please. The art of tattoo
is an ancient rite of mankind, by far older than modern medicine and open
wound surgery. I assume that the latter causes, in magnitudes of order, far
more severe infections than tattoos.
PS. I assume there are a lot of tattoo parlors in Sherman, Texas. If there,
however, is only one, it would be a shame to indirectly reveal its
identification as long as cruise ships and hotels serving as transient
reservoirs for legionellosis are kept anonymous by ProMED-mail.
--
Hakon Haaheim, M.Sc
Institute of Microbiology
HQ Defence Command Norway
Joint Medical Services
