Date: Thu, 30 Jul 1998 16:17:16 -0600
From: Elayne Angel <angel@ringsofdesire.com>

I would like to respond to Joe Shea's article on the topic of infection
risk in piercing and tattooing as seen in the American Reporter, Oklahoma
City.
While it is true that there is potential for disease transmission from any
event which breaks the skin, the manner in which it is accomplished is
highly relevant. It is vital to become an educated consumer of body art
services, to ask the right questions and be certain your health and safety
is assured.
A skilled and caring professional piercer uses appropriate precautions to
prevent exposure to disease-causing microorganisms during all procedures.
We adhere to established Universal Precautions Procedures, including the
wearing of disposable latex gloves for all client contact. Instruments are
sterilized in individual packets prior to use in a Pelton-Crane Steam
Autoclave which is spore-tested weekly. (Documentation is on file, and is
available by request).
Our piercing needles are, of course, single use. Along with our
biohazardous paper waste, they are picked up and appropriately disposed of
by BFI, our Biohazardous Waste Disposal company. (Documentation is on file,
and is available by request).
The marking pen used in the piercing procedure (even on unbroken or
non-mucous membrane skin) is single use. We work from a sterile field, and
use only products from single-use disposable packets. Supplies are
handled only with freshly gloved hands, and are wiped down at the beginning
of each day with MadaCide (liquid hospital disinfectant/cleaner) and Super
Sani-cloths (germicidal-impregnated wipes).
Workstations are completely wiped down at the beginning of the day, and
after each client with Super Sani-cloths and MadaCide.
Jewelry is individually packaged and autoclaved prior to use. Because the
jewelry packets are handled at the retail counter, once the contents are
opened onto the sterile field, gloves are changed.
The utmost care is taken with each client to assure an aseptic procedure.
We pierce many medical professionals who routinely comment that we are much
more stringently hygienic than the hospitals and medical offices in which
they work!
There is no more cause for concern of disease transmission to any client of
Rings of Desire as a result of piercing than there would be from donating
blood or plasma.
--
